      • setRows

        public void setRows(ByteBuffer rows,
           Covenant promise)
             throws IOException
        Inserts or updates the given rows. The rows are passed in en bloc: they may be ordered in any way. The operation is fail-safe (all-or-nothing).

        Pay attention to the promise parameter. It has a huge impact on performance, but just as importantly, if you break the promise, you break the data set.

        Parameters:
        rows - the remaining bytes in this buffer represent the rows being input. The remaining bytes must be an exact multiple of the row width. If the same row (recall, the identity of a row is defined by the table's RowOrder) occurs twice in this buffer, then the last occurance wins.
        promise - declares how and whether the caller agrees not to later modify the given rows parameter. If the caller breaks the promise, then the table will almost certainly get corrupted!. May be null (no promise), but that would be a shame.
        Throws:
        IOException

      • discardFile

        protected void discardFile(File file)
        Discards a no-longer used file. Use this as a customization hook to build such things as audit trails, etc. The base implementation just deletes the file.
        Throws:
        IOException - the base implementation doesn't throw this
        IllegalStateException - if the file cannot be moved to the trash directory

        public SidTableSet load(CommitRecord record)

      • loadSortedTable

        public SidTable loadSortedTable(long tableId)
                         throws IOException
        Loads an existing sorted table. If the table had some sort of header, here's where you'd handle that. The base implementation assumes no header. The caller must arrange that the returned instance be eventually closed; otherwise, a resource leak will occur.
        Returns:
        a read-only instance
        Throws:
        IOException
